 with authorization2star  aA sweeping history of the American invention of modern money. Economists endlessly debate the nature of legal tender monetary systems—coins and bills issued by a government or other authority. Yet the origins of these currencies have received little attention. Dror Goldberg tells the story of modern money in North America through the Massachusetts colony during the seventeenth century. As the young settlement transitioned to self-governance and its economy grew, the need to formalize a smooth exchange emerged. Printing local money followed. Easy Money illustrates how colonists invented contemporary currency by shifting its foundation from intrinsically valuable goods—such as silver—to the taxation of the state. Goldberg traces how this structure grew into a worldwide system in which, monetarily, we are all Massachusetts. Weaving economics, law, and American history, Easy Money is a new touchstone in the story of monetary systems.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mai 2023) 0aLegal tenderzUnited StatesxHistoryy17th century. 0aMonetary policyzEnglandxHistoryy16th century. 0aMonetary policyzMassachusettsxHistoryy17th century. 0aMoneyzUnited StatesxHistoryy17th century. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079732940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226825113423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226825113/original  a978-3-11-079732-9  University of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles